(Principle
    "Repeated similar intent records carry stronger signal. The data model expresses intent intensity through repetition rather than a per-record intensity field — if the psyche restates an intent, that restatement is itself evidence of greater conviction. Query-time clustering on summary similarity surfaces 'how many times has the psyche said this' as the read-side signal."
    "repeated similar intents will mean stronger signal"
    "Rationale embedded in the Q1 answer: signal-by-repetition is why separate records beat aggregate records — repetition itself is the load-bearing primitive."
    Maximum
    2026-05-19T17:30:00Z)

(Correction
    "Inside persona-spirit, intent is the component's domain. Type names must NOT prefix `Intent` — that's repetition of the component's namespace. The Entry-not-IntentEntry correction (intent#19) generalises: every type in signal-persona-spirit currently starting with `Intent` drops the prefix unless removing it produces genuine ambiguity. Examples: IntentRecordIdentifier → RecordIdentifier; IntentTopic → Topic; IntentSummary → Summary; IntentQuote → Quote; IntentContext → Context; IntentObservationMode → ObservationMode; IntentRecordObservation → RecordObservation; IntentRecordSummary → RecordSummary; IntentRecordProvenance → RecordProvenance; IntentRecordCaptured → RecordCaptured."
    "The type intent record identifier is not good because spirit deals with intent. So it's repetition to say intent record identifier. At most it should be record identifier, if we even say record."
    "Resolving Q2 of /236. Generalising intent#19 across the contract: every Intent-prefixed type drops the prefix; the domain is implicit from the crate."
    Maximum
    2026-05-19T17:30:00Z)

